In the palette there is the *Forms *section with several form elements. Forms enable interactions in documents.

## Text Field (Single-Line) / Text Area (Multi-Line)
Text field and text area are single-line or multi-line input fields in which both alphanumeric and numeric characters can be entered. In case of a multi-line text area, the value *Multiline *is preselected for the options attribute. The representation of the two text fields in the editor can be seen on the following screenshot:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

By clicking on the text in the text field, you can edit the text it contains. When inserting the text fields, a name is generated by the system by default. Under *Style &amp; Properties*, you can edit the following attributes in the *Form Field *section:

**Attribute**

**Description**

Text

Initial text, which is displayed in the field (can be edited directly in the editor)

Max Length

Maximum number of characters of the field

Read only (Options)

The field can not be edited

Required (Options)

The field is required

**Attribute**

**Description**

Multiline (Options)

Defines a multi-line input field, i.e. users are allowed to insert line breaks and text may be wrapped in several lines

Do not scroll (Options)

Determines if a scrollbar should appear when the content is too big

Password (Options)

The entered characters are masked (password field)

File selection (Options)

Display a file selection instead of a field

Do not spell check (Options)

Disables the spellcheck of the PDF reader for this field

Edit (Options)

Determines if users shall be able to edit the field content

The *Text field *element can be configured to display a date field with calendar selection in the Composer.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

To support a date input, configure the *content-type *attribute of the *Text Field *element via *Style &amp; Properties *&gt; Advanced &gt; *Miscellaneous *by setting the value as *date*. When the *content_type *is set without any formatting pattern, calendar date formatting will be performed according to the systems environment. The most common date pattern *DDMMYYYY *can be set to the property *Miscellaneous &gt; content-type *as ***date:DD.MM.YYYY***. The *format pattern *for the *content-type *must be in the syntax permitted by [*moment.js*](https://momentjs.com/docs/)*  *library.

The date-picker can also adapt custom formats defined by the user. There are a wide range of options that can be used to format different components of the date (day, month, year). For instance, you can display date as default value by setting the date and its format via `Advanced &gt; Miscellaneous &gt; Form Field &gt; formfield-text_`. The attribute *formfield-text *can also be defined using an XPath expression. For example, you can format and display the current date as the default calendar value in the date input field.

## Combobox / Listbox
The elements Combobox and Listbox can be inserted in the editor or the outline using drag &amp; drop. Immediately after the insertion, a dialog appears in which the *Choices *and *Values *data can be entered. To add a new choice, press the Enter key in the value field of the last choice. You can remove a choice by clicking on the pencil icon to the right of the value field.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

After clicking on *Create*, the Combobox is displayed in the editor as follows:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Clicking on the Combobox opens the list with all existing choices. And the choices that is to be displayed at the beginning can be defined. The choices can also be defined under `Style &amp; Properties &gt; Form Field`* *in the *Selection *field. Attention, it starts with the 0th line (1st optical line = selection 0, 2nd optical line = selection 1 etc.).

The choices of the Listbox are visualized directly in the editor.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

If the choices have be changed after the elements have been created, you can do this under `Style &amp; Properties &gt; Form Field`* *section by clicking on the three dots next to the *Selection *field.

> Note

*Note that backslash characters (\) need to be escaped by duplicating them (\\).*

## Radio-button / Checkbox
After inserting the radio-button element in the editor or outline, a dialog appears in which the number of radio buttons can be defined and the option *Create group *can be activated.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Given that a Radio-button normally always should have at least a second Radio-button as the opponent, the membership of the various Radio-buttons must be specified through their names. This means, that multiple Radio-buttons are supposed to have the same name but different values. When a Radio-button is selected, the value of the respective button is transmitted.

If *Create group *was activated in the dialog, the names of the buttons are automatically adapted and only one button at the time can be selected within the group. Radio buttons can be preselected for initialization directly in the editor by clicking on the respective button.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Under *Style &amp; Properties *in the *Form Field *section, attributes such as *Field Name*, *Check-type *(appearance of the button), *Checked *(preselection of the button) and *Value *(value that is transmitted upon activation) can be edited.

The ***Checkbox ***element is similar to the radio buttons. When inserting a checkbox, no dialog appears and the attributes can be edited under *Style &amp; Properties *in the *Form Field *section. The checkboxes can also be preselected directly in the editor. All checkboxes with the same name are activated / deactivated at the same time.

## Button
The *Button *element can be used to create buttons in the template. The button is visualized in the editor as follows:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The attributes of the button can be edited under *Style &amp; Properties *in the *Form Field *section. The attributes *Field Name *(designation of the button), *Width *and *Height *(in mm) and *Text *(display text) are important.

A Button can contain a *script*, which can be used to interact with other form elements to e.g. transmit data. In order to add one, just drag and drop the element Script from the Palette to the button.

## Script
The processing of form or the graphic elements takes place via scripts that are created in JavaScript. To do this, Script must first be selected as the script type (can be found under *Style &amp; Properties *in the *Script *section). The code itself is then entered in the *Details *field. The code can either be entered directly in the field, or you can open the input mask by clicking on the three dots next to the *Details *field. JavaScript entries are validated in this mask.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Scripts for graphic elements
The scripts, which are stored below graphical elements, are always linked to an event. Please use a different script for each event.

### Script attributes
### Action type
**Action type**

**Description**

hide

Hides the form elements listed in the details field or all fields if left empty

reset

Form is reset

script

Individual coding in JavaScript

show

Shows the form elements listed in the details field or all fields if left empty

submit

Form is submitted

### Options
This option is used to declare additional properties (e.g which type of data) for submit and reset. Most commonly used Options are listed and described below

**Option**

**Description**

*reset_exclude*

Excludes the Form elements listed in the

*details_field *from the reset action

*submit_html_format*

Sends HTML data with POST

*submit_html_get*

Sends HTML data with GET

*submit_pdf*

Sends the complete Pdf document

*submit_xfdf*

Sends data as XFDF (XML format)

### Target
The address for the web service that processes the data on submit is entered in the Target field.

### Events / Trigger
The link between scripts and fields takes place via Events. If e.g. a mouse button in a field is pressed or the field is exited, the system triggers an event that is encrypted using the Trigger.

The following table shows all available Events and their Triggers. The list is sorted in the order which event occurs first and is processed by the system:

**Trigger**

**Event**

**Description**

E

Mouse Enter

Mouse pointer moves into the field

X

Mouse Exit

Mouse pointer leaves the field

D

Mouse Down

Mouse button is pressed on the field

F

Focus

Field receives focus

U

Mouse Up

Mouse button is released on the field

K

Keystroke

A key is pressed in the field

K

SelectionChange

Selection has changed (only for the listbox and combobox)

V

Validate

Entry is complete - field can be checked

B

Blur

Field loses focus

### Example Validate
The JavaScript code can be accessed directly on the event information event. The following examples show various input validations, which are anchored at the Validate event (*Trigger *= V). An acoustic signal is generated, a message is displayed and the return code is set to false at each error. The last one prevents the user from exiting the field.

At Validate, the entered value has not yet been transferred in the field and thus it has to be

queried through event.value.

Numeric entry (allowed: 0-9, comma and period):

`var value = "" + event.value.replace(/[^,.\d]/g, "");
if (value.length &lt; event.value.length || !isFinite(value)) { 
   app.beep(0);
   app.alert("Invalid value in field" + event.target.name); 
   event.rc = false; 
}`Input between 0 and 100 allowed:

`if (event.value &lt; 0 || event.value &gt; 100) { 
   app.beep(0);
   app.alert("Value must be between 0 and 100"); 
   event.rc = false;
}`### Further information

## Signature
The signature field can be added to allow users to sign a document in Composer, or to create a signature field in the PDF. Note that not all PDF viewers support signature fields, especially viewers embedded in browsers. For best results, it is recommended to view the preview PDF in an external viewer. Use the "Open externally" button of the preview window for this.

The signature is displayed in the editor with the example name "John Doe":
